{"title_page": "Ravi Pillay", "text_new": "{{short description|South African attorney and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Ravi Pillay\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of the Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Finance]]\n| premier             = [[Sihle Zikalala]]\n| term_start          = 27 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Belinda Scott]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Human Settlements and Public Works]]\n| premier1            = [[Willies Mchunu]]<br/>[[Senzo Mchunu]]<br/>[[Zweli Mkhize]]\n| term_start1         = 15 November 2011\n| term_end1           = 27 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Maggie Govender]]\n| successor1          = [[Peggy Nkonyeni]]\n| office2             = Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n| term_start2         = 6 May 2009\n| term_end2           = \n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| birthname           = Ravigasen Ranganathan Pillay\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1958|11|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Port Shepstone]], [[Natal Province]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Durban-Westville]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = Attorney<br/>Politician\n| known_for           = \n| committees          = \n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Ravigasen Ranganathan \"Ravi\" Pillay''' (born 19 November 1958) is a South African attorney and [[African National Congress]] (ANC) politician who is the Member of the Executive Council for Finance in [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Government]], appointed in May 2019. He was previously the MEC for Human Settlements and Public Works from 2011 to 2019. Pillay was elected a Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]] in 2009 and served as the legislature's chief whip of the majority party from 2009 to 2011.\n==Biography==\nPillay was born on 19 November 1958 in [[Port Shepstone]] in the [[Natal Province]]. He studied at the [[University of Durban-Westville]] and obtained a BA LLB. He was a student activist at the university and joined the ANC in 1981. He was part of a peace committee on the south coast.<ref name=\"kzntreasury\">{{cite web |title=Profile of MEC Ravi Pillay |url=http://www.kzntreasury.gov.za/AboutUs/SitePages/KwaZulu-Natal%20Treasury%20-%20MEC%20Profile.aspx |website=KZN Treasury |accessdate=24 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424210301/http://www.kzntreasury.gov.za/AboutUs/SitePages/KwaZulu-Natal%20Treasury%20-%20MEC%20Profile.aspx |archivedate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter apartheid, Pillay became the inaugural speaker of the [[Hibiscus Coast Local Municipality]] and was later promoted to be speaker of the [[Ugu District Municipality]].<ref name=\"kzntreasury\" />\n\nHe was elected an MPL in May 2009 and became the chief whip of the ANC caucus in the legislature. Later, in November 2011, he was appointed to the province's Executive Council as the member for Human Settlements and Public Works. He served in the post from 2011 to 2019 under three premiers: [[Zweli Mkhize]], [[Senzo Mchunu]] and [[Willies Mchunu]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zikalala |first1=Sihle |title=ANC KZN backs Mkhize's cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/anc-kzn-backs-mkhizes-cabinet-reshuffle |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=15 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mchunu |first1=Senzo |title=The new KZN cabinet - Senzo Mchunu |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-kzn-cabinet--senzo-mchunu |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATED: Cabinet reshuffle in KwaZulu-Natal |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/cabinet-reshuffle-in-kwazulu-natal |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 June 2016 |location=Durban}}</ref>\n\nPillay was appointed acting premier in March 2018 and became the first [[Indian South African]] to hold the post. He has since been acting premier on multiple occasions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marriah - Maharaj |first1=Jolene |title=LOOK: MEC Ravi Pillay sworn is as KZN Acting Premier |url=https://www.iol.co.za/thepost/community-news/look-mec-ravi-pillay-sworn-is-as-kzn-acting-premier-31759649 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pillay became the new MEC for Finance in the cabinet of [[Sihle Zikalala]]. He succeeded [[Belinda Scott]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Kaveel |title=Premier Sihle Zikalala announces his KZN cabinet |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/premier-sihle-zikalala-announces-his-kzn-cabinet-20190527 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://kznlegislature.gov.za/members/hon-rr-pillay/ Hon. RR Pillay \u2013 KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/rr-pillay/ Ravigasen Ranganathan Pillay \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pillay, Ravi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:South African politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Durban-Westville alumni]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African attorney and politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Ravi Pillay\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of the Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Finance]]\n| premier             = [[Sihle Zikalala]]\n| term_start          = 27 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Belinda Scott]]\n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Human Settlements and Public Works]]\n| premier1            = [[Willies Mchunu]]<br/>[[Senzo Mchunu]]<br/>[[Zweli Mkhize]]\n| term_start1         = 15 November 2011\n| term_end1           = 27 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Maggie Govender]]\n| successor1          = [[Peggy Nkonyeni]]\n| office2             = Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n| term_start2         = 6 May 2009\n| term_end2           = \n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| birthname           = Ravigasen Ranganathan Pillay\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1958|11|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Port Shepstone]], [[Natal Province]]\n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Durban-Westville]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = Attorney<br/>Politician\n| known_for           = \n| committees          = \n| portfolio           = \n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Ravigasen Ranganathan \"Ravi\" Pillay''' (born 19 November 1958) is a South African attorney and [[African National Congress]] (ANC) politician who is the Member of the Executive Council for Finance in [[Executive Council (South Africa)#KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal Provincial Government]], appointed in May 2019. He was previously the MEC for Human Settlements and Public Works from 2011 to 2019. Pillay was elected a Member of the [[KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]] in 2009 and served as the legislature's chief whip of the majority party from 2009 to 2011.\n==Biography==\nPillay was born on 19 November 1958 in [[Port Shepstone]] in the [[Natal Province]]. He studied at the [[University of Durban-Westville]] and obtained a BA LLB. He was a student activist at the university and joined the ANC in 1981. He was part of a peace committee on the south coast.<ref name=\"kzntreasury\">{{cite web |title=Profile of MEC Ravi Pillay |url=http://www.kzntreasury.gov.za/AboutUs/SitePages/KwaZulu-Natal%20Treasury%20-%20MEC%20Profile.aspx |website=KZN Treasury |accessdate=24 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424210301/http://www.kzntreasury.gov.za/AboutUs/SitePages/KwaZulu-Natal%20Treasury%20-%20MEC%20Profile.aspx |archivedate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter apartheid, Pillay became the inaugural speaker of the [[Hibiscus Coast Local Municipality]] and was later promoted to be speaker of the [[Ugu District Municipality]].<ref name=\"kzntreasury\" />\n\nHe was elected an MPL in May 2009 and became the chief whip of the ANC caucus in the legislature. Later, in November 2011, he was appointed to the province's Executive Council as the member for Human Settlements and Public Works. He served in the post from 2011 to 2019 under three premiers: [[Zweli Mkhize]], [[Senzo Mchunu]] and [[Willies Mchunu]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zikalala |first1=Sihle |title=ANC KZN backs Mkhize's cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/anc-kzn-backs-mkhizes-cabinet-reshuffle |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=15 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mchunu |first1=Senzo |title=The new KZN cabinet - Senzo Mchunu |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-kzn-cabinet--senzo-mchunu |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=UPDATED: Cabinet reshuffle in KwaZulu-Natal |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/cabinet-reshuffle-in-kwazulu-natal |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 June 2016 |location=Durban}}</ref>\n\nPillay was appointed acting premier in March 2018 and became the first [[[Indian South African]] to hold the post. He has since been acting premier on multiple occasions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marriah - Maharaj |first1=Jolene |title=LOOK: MEC Ravi Pillay sworn is as KZN Acting Premier |url=https://www.iol.co.za/thepost/community-news/look-mec-ravi-pillay-sworn-is-as-kzn-acting-premier-31759649 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Pillay became the new MEC for Finance in the cabinet of [[Sihle Zikalala]]. He succeeded [[Belinda Scott]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Kaveel |title=Premier Sihle Zikalala announces his KZN cabinet |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/premier-sihle-zikalala-announces-his-kzn-cabinet-20190527 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://kznlegislature.gov.za/members/hon-rr-pillay/ Hon. RR Pillay \u2013 KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/rr-pillay/ Ravigasen Ranganathan Pillay \u2013 People's Assembly]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pillay, Ravi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the KwaZulu-Natal Legislature]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:South African politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Durban-Westville alumni]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ravi_Pillay"}
{"title_page": "Jordan Love", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Jordan Love\n| alt                 = \n| number              = 10\n| current_team        = Green Bay Packers\n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|11|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bakersfield, California]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 4\n| weight_lb           = 224\n| high_school         = [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n| college             = [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 26\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n*Second-team All-[[Mountain West Conference|MWC]] ([[2018 Mountain West Conference football season|2018]])\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n'''Jordan Love''' (born November 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] and was drafted by the Packers in the first round of the [[2020 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early years==\nJordan Love was born in [[Bakersfield, California]] on November 2, 1998. When Love was 14 years old, his father, Orbin Love, committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Love fulfilling his late father's vision |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001101587/article/utah-states-jordan-love-fulfilling-his-late-fathers-vision |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> Love attended [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty High School]]. After being told he could not play quarterback as a freshman, Love was named the starter by his senior year. As a senior, Love passed for 2,148 yards and 24 [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 806 yards with eight touchdowns.  He committed to play college football at [[Utah State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cachevalleydaily.com/news/archive/2015/06/23/161ccb22-192b-11e5-bf8c-43d84855b203/|title=\"Dual-threat\" quarterback from California commits to USU}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nLove [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his first year at Utah State in 2016. As a redshirt freshman in 2017, he played in 12 games and started the final six.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/transformed-and-recharged-jordan-love-takes-off-as-freshman-qb/article_92f1e2e4-e5d0-11e7-821f-effdc3faa0bd.html|title=Transformed and recharged, Jordan Love takes off as freshman QB at Utah State|first=TREVOR HORN|last=thorn@bakersfield.com|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> He finished the season, completing 129 of 235 passes for 1,631 yards, eight touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900022375/utah-state-position-breakdown-jordan-love-looks-to-make-strides-as-undisputed-starting-qb.html|title=Utah State position breakdown: Jordan Love looks to make strides as undisputed starting QB|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=June 21, 2018|website=Deseret News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900027319/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-a-completely-different-guy-headed-into-2018-season.html|title=Utah State QB Jordan Love a 'completely different guy' heading into 2018 season|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=August 8, 2018|website=Deseret News}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2018, Love started all 13 games, completing 267 of 417 passes for a school season record 3,567 yards with 32 touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900048926/usu-football-jordan-love-and-david-woodward-named-to-2019-touchdown-club-of-columbus-players-to-watch-list.html|title=USU football: Jordan Love and David Woodward named to 2019 Touchdown Club of Columbus Players to Watch List|date=January 3, 2019|website=Deseret News}}</ref> He was named the MVP of the [[2018 New Mexico Bowl]] after passing for 359 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/bvarsity/liberty-graduate-leads-utah-state-to-blowout-bowl-win/article_33acd7ae-00c2-11e9-91a4-9bcb24e40661.html|title=Liberty graduate leads Utah State to blowout bowl win|first=STAFF AND WIRE|last=REPORT|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> Following the end of the 2019 season, Love announced that he would forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28270139/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-declares-nfl-draft.html. |title=Utah State QB Jordan Love declares for NFL draft |date=December 10, 2019 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\u00be\n|       weight = 224\n|         dash = 4.74\n|    ten split = \n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle = 4.52\n|   cone drill = 7.21\n|     vertical = 35.5\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 10\n|        bench =\n|     arm span = 32\u215d\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|    wonderlic =\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jordan-love?id=32194c4f-5613-0776-be4c-ce231b05c522 |title=Jordan Love Combine Profile |publisher=National Football League |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\nLove was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the first round with the 26th overall pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]]. The Packers moved up from their 30th overall selection in a trade with the [[Miami Dolphins]], who acquired the pick in a trade with the [[Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.packers.com/news/2020-nfl-draft-packers-select-utah-state-qb-jordan-love-in-first-round-no-26-ove|title=2020 NFL Draft: Packers select Utah State QB Jordan Love in first round, No. 26 overall|website=packers.com|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://utahstateaggies.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3437 Utah State Aggies bio]\n\n{{Utah State Aggies quarterback navbox}}\n{{2020 NFL Draft}}\n{{PackersFirstPick}}\n{{Packers2020DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love, Jordan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bakersfield, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Utah State Aggies football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Jordan Love\n| alt                 = \n| number              = 10\n| current_team        = Green Bay Packers\n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|11|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Bakersfield, California]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 4\n| weight_lb           = 224\n| high_school         = [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty]] (Bakersfield, California)\n| college             = [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 1\n| draftpick           = 26\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n*Second-team All-[[Mountain West Conference|MWC]] ([[2018 Mountain West Conference football season|2018]])\n*New Mexico Bowl MVP ([[2018 New Mexico Bowl|2018]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 = \n}}\n'''Jordan Love''' (born November 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] and was drafted by the Packers in the first round of the [[2020 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early years==\nJordan Love was born in [[Bakersfield, California]] on November 2, 1998. When Love was 14 years old, Love's father, Orbin Love, committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Love fulfilling his late father's vision |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001101587/article/utah-states-jordan-love-fulfilling-his-late-fathers-vision |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> Love attended [[Liberty High School (Bakersfield, California)|Liberty High School]]. After being told he could not play quarterback as a freshman, Love was named the starter by his senior year. As a senior, Love passed for 2,148 yards and 24 [[touchdowns]] and rushed for 806 yards with eight touchdowns.  He committed to play college football at [[Utah State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cachevalleydaily.com/news/archive/2015/06/23/161ccb22-192b-11e5-bf8c-43d84855b203/|title=\"Dual-threat\" quarterback from California commits to USU}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nLove [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]] his first year at Utah State in 2016. As a redshirt freshman in 2017, he played in 12 games and started the final six.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/transformed-and-recharged-jordan-love-takes-off-as-freshman-qb/article_92f1e2e4-e5d0-11e7-821f-effdc3faa0bd.html|title=Transformed and recharged, Jordan Love takes off as freshman QB at Utah State|first=TREVOR HORN|last=thorn@bakersfield.com|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> He finished the season, completing 129 of 235 passes for 1,631 yards, eight touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900022375/utah-state-position-breakdown-jordan-love-looks-to-make-strides-as-undisputed-starting-qb.html|title=Utah State position breakdown: Jordan Love looks to make strides as undisputed starting QB|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=June 21, 2018|website=Deseret News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900027319/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-a-completely-different-guy-headed-into-2018-season.html|title=Utah State QB Jordan Love a 'completely different guy' heading into 2018 season|first=Lafe|last=Peavler|date=August 8, 2018|website=Deseret News}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2018, Love started all 13 games, completing 267 of 417 passes for a school season record 3,567 yards with 32 touchdowns and six interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900048926/usu-football-jordan-love-and-david-woodward-named-to-2019-touchdown-club-of-columbus-players-to-watch-list.html|title=USU football: Jordan Love and David Woodward named to 2019 Touchdown Club of Columbus Players to Watch List|date=January 3, 2019|website=Deseret News}}</ref> He was named the MVP of the [[2018 New Mexico Bowl]] after passing for 359 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/sports/bvarsity/liberty-graduate-leads-utah-state-to-blowout-bowl-win/article_33acd7ae-00c2-11e9-91a4-9bcb24e40661.html|title=Liberty graduate leads Utah State to blowout bowl win|first=STAFF AND WIRE|last=REPORT|website=The Bakersfield Californian}}</ref> Following the end of the 2019 season, Love announced that he would forgo his senior year by declaring for the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28270139/utah-state-qb-jordan-love-declares-nfl-draft.html. |title=Utah State QB Jordan Love declares for NFL draft |date=December 10, 2019 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\u00be\n|       weight = 224\n|         dash = 4.74\n|    ten split = \n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle = 4.52\n|   cone drill = 7.21\n|     vertical = 35.5\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 10\n|        bench =\n|     arm span = 32\u215d\n|    hand span = 10\u00bd\n|    wonderlic =\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jordan-love?id=32194c4f-5613-0776-be4c-ce231b05c522 |title=Jordan Love Combine Profile |publisher=National Football League |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\nLove was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the first round with the 26th overall pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]]. The Packers moved up from their 30th overall selection in a trade with the [[Miami Dolphins]], who acquired the pick in a trade with the [[Houston Texans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.packers.com/news/2020-nfl-draft-packers-select-utah-state-qb-jordan-love-in-first-round-no-26-ove|title=2020 NFL Draft: Packers select Utah State QB Jordan Love in first round, No. 26 overall|website=packers.com|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://utahstateaggies.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3437 Utah State Aggies bio]\n\n{{Utah State Aggies quarterback navbox}}\n{{2020 NFL Draft}}\n{{PackersFirstPick}}\n{{Packers2020DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love, Jordan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bakersfield, California]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from California]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Utah State Aggies football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n", "name_user": "Imdabes7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jordan_Love"}
{"title_page": "Cheraw, South Carolina", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cheraw, South Carolina\n|settlement_type          = [[Town]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = CherawSC.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = SCMap-doton-Cheraw.PNG\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Cheraw, South Carolina\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[South Carolina]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in South Carolina|Counties]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Chesterfield County, South Carolina|Chesterfield]], [[Marlboro County, South Carolina|Marlboro]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 14.1\n|area_land_km2            = 14.0\n|area_water_km2           = 0.1\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 5851\n|population_density_km2   = 416.6\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 51\n|elevation_ft             = 167\n|coordinates              = {{coord|34|41|48|N|79|53|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 29520\n|area_code                = [[Area codes 843 and 854|843, 854]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 45-13600<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1247267<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|www.cheraw.com}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n[[Image:Cheraw Town Hall.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Historic Town Hall in downtown Cheraw]]\n[[Image:Cheraw British Grave.jpg|thumb|right|The grave marker for a British soldier in St.&nbsp;David's Cemetery]]\n\n'''Cheraw''' ({{IPAc-en|t\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0254\u02d0}} {{respell|ch\u0259|RAW|'}}, {{IPAc-en|local|\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0254\u02d0}} {{respell|sh\u0259|RAW|'}}) is a town on the [[Pee Dee River]] in [[Chesterfield County, South Carolina|Chesterfield]] County [[South Carolina]], United States. The population was 5,851 at the 2010 census and has the lowest per capita income level of any municipality of 5,000 or more residents in the Pee Dee region.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4513600| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Cheraw town, South Carolina| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=July 1, 2015| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213045507/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4513600| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It has been nicknamed \"The Prettiest Town in Dixie\". The harbor tug ''[[USS Cheraw (YTB-802)|USS Cheraw]]'' was named in the town's honor.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nWhen the first Europeans arrived in the area it was inhabited by the [[Cheraw]] and [[Pee Dee people|Pee Dee]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]] tribes. The Cheraw lived near the waterfall hill, near present-day Cheraw, but by the 1730s they had been devastated by new infectious disease inadvertently carried by the European traders. Survivors joined the [[Catawba people|Catawba Confederacy]] for safety and left their name in history. Only a few scattered Cheraw families remained by the time of the [[American Revolution]]. A few European settlers entered their territory in the 1730s, forced upriver when the [[Wales|Welsh]] came to claim the Welsh [[Baptist]] lands granted by the English government in the area around [[Society Hill, South Carolina|Society Hill]]. Many of the early settlers of the 1740s in Cheraw were ethnic [[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scots]], [[French people|French]] [[Huguenots]], or [[Irish people|Scots-Irish]].\n\nBy 1750, Cheraw had become an established Anglo-American village with a growing river trade, one of the first inland villages. It was one of only six places in South Carolina that appeared on English maps at the time. In the 1760s, Joseph and Eli Kershaw were granted the part of Cheraw that is now the downtown historic district. The Kershaws laid out a formal street system. By 1830 settlers lined all the streets with rows of [[Ulmus americana|elms]]. The Kershaws originally called the town \"Chatham\", but people never accepted this name, continuing to call it \"Cheraw\" or \"Cheraw Hill\".\n\n===American Revolution===\nThere was a lack of organization and rule during the beginning of the 1740s in the backcountry of South Carolina. This lack of organization and unrest was an underlying cause of the resentment people of these areas felt toward the British Crown. In the Pee Dee area, planters organized a group called [[War of the Regulation|the Regulators]] to help bring order to the area. In 1768 [[St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery|St. David's Parish]], the last [[Anglican Church]] built in South Carolina under [[King George III]], was established to help serve the civic and religious needs of the Cheraw area. Later a judicial district and courthouse were established to help deal with the problem of order. However, there was still much discontent with the ruling authority, and in May 1776 the grand jury of the Cheraws District Two declared its independence from [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]].\n\nMany area men played prominent roles in the [[American Revolution]]. They included Claudius Pegues, General Henry W. Harrington, the Ellerbe brothers, Philip Pledger, and Eli Kershaw. There was much unrest in the area during this time because Cheraw fell into part of the British strategic line of defense, where [[garrison]]s were built to control revolutionaries and to encourage [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyalists]]. Other towns in this line of defense included [[Camden, South Carolina]], and [[Augusta, Georgia]]. Cheraw also became a strategic point for the Americans. Military activity was especially heavy in Cheraw and surrounding counties from 1780-1781. During the Revolutionary War, [[St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery|St. David's Church]] was used as a hospital for British troops that operated under [[Lord Cornwallis]]'s command and as quarters for the South Carolina militia. In December 1780, just across from Cheraw, American commander General [[Nathanael Greene]] set up a \"camp of repose\" to rest and train his men.\n\n===Early 19th century===\nIn 1819, the first [[steamboat]] came up river, and along with it a burst of prosperity because of expanded trade. Cheraw was incorporated as a town in 1820. The main crops from the Cheraw area were [[Maize|corn]], [[cotton]], [[tobacco]], [[rice]] and [[indigo]]. Cheraw had the largest cotton market between [[Georgetown, South Carolina]], and [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]. Because of the cotton trade, the town boasted the largest bank in South Carolina outside of [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] before the Civil War. Despite a serious fire in 1835, by 1850 the town was a prosperous center of trade.\n\n===Civil War===\n<!-- Missing image removed: [[Image:Cheraw Confederate Monument.jpg|thumb|right|The Confederate Monument in Cheraw is the oldest in the country.]] -->\nLeading up to the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Cheraw citizens played a key role in South Carolina's secession from the Union. On November 19, 1860, the first call for secession in a public meeting was made at the Chesterfield County Courthouse. John A. Inglis of Cheraw was in attendance. He later introduced the resolution for South Carolina to secede. Inglis was also named the chairman of the committee that wrote the document for South Carolina's secession.\n\nFrom the beginning of the war, Cheraw was known as a place of refuge and a storehouse for valuables. In March 1865, General [[William T. Sherman]] brought his [[Union Army|Union]] troops to Cheraw for several days. One Union soldier said that they found Cheraw to be \"a pleasant town and an old one with the Southern aristocratic bearing.\" Sherman used this as a time to gain more control over his men. No private dwellings or public buildings in Cheraw were destroyed by Sherman and his troops. However, an accidental explosion of captured gunpowder at the river hill burned the Cheraw business district. The county courthouse in [[Chesterfield, South Carolina|Chesterfield]] was burned in this event, resulting in the loss of many records. Thus, it is difficult to date many of the historic properties.\n\nDuring the Civil War, St.&nbsp;David's Church was used as a hospital by both the [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] and Union armies. Some troops from both armies were buried there. The first Confederate monument was erected there in 1867, a claim disputed by [[Confederate Memorial (Romney, West Virginia)|Romney, West Virginia]]. Originally, the monument did not mention the Confederate soldiers because the area was still occupied by Federal troops.\n\n===20th century to present===\n\nThe Civil War caused great economic hardship in Cheraw, as it did in the entire South. However, by the early 1900s, prosperity began to return to Cheraw. The Great Depression again brought change. [[Cheraw State Park]] and Sandhills State Forest were both founded in the 1930s. By the 1950s and 1960s the groundwork was laid for industrial growth. By the end of the 20th century, Cheraw had a balanced industrial base while maintaining its historic charm, architectural treasures and natural resources.\n\nIn November, 1941, Cheraw saw pretend combat in its streets during the Battle of Pee Dee River, Phase 1 of the Carolina Maneuvers.  General George Patton's 2nd Armored Division was the (Red) attacking force versus Major General Charles F. Thompson's I Corps defending (Blue).  Tanks from Patton's division penetrated the defenses and entered the city center to be met by defending anti-tank guns.  It was determined that Red's tanks were successful and Blue forces were forced to withdraw from the town.<ref>Page 139, \"The U.S. Army GHQ Maneuvers of 1941\", Christopher R. Gabel,</ref>\n\nIn addition to St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery, the [[Cheraw Historic District]] and [[Robert Smalls School]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name=\"nps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/nr/listings/20140314.htm|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|date=2014-03-14|work=Weekly List of Actions Taken on Properties: 3/03/14 through 3/07/14|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCheraw is located in eastern Chesterfield County at the [[Atlantic Seaboard fall line|fall line]] of the [[Pee Dee River]]. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|14.1|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|14.0|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.1|km2|order=flip|2}}, or 0.64%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n[[U.S. Route 1]] passes through the center of the town, leading northeast {{convert|21|mi}} to [[Rockingham, North Carolina]], and southwest {{convert|55|mi}} to [[Camden, South Carolina|Camden]]. [[U.S. Route 52]] joins US 1 in the center of Cheraw but leads northwest {{convert|22|mi}} to [[Wadesboro, North Carolina]], and south {{convert|41|mi}} to [[Florence, South Carolina|Florence]]. [[South Carolina Highway 9]] also passes through the center of Cheraw, leading southeast {{convert|15|mi}} to [[Bennettsville, South Carolina|Bennettsville]] and west {{convert|12|mi}} to [[Chesterfield, South Carolina|Chesterfield]], the [[county seat]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|align=right\n|1880= 918\n|1890= 976\n|1900= 1151\n|1910= 2873\n|1920= 3150\n|1930= 3573\n|1940= 4497\n|1950= 4836\n|1960= 5171\n|1970= 5627\n|1980= 5654\n|1990= 5505\n|2000= 5524\n|2010= 5851\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=5619\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=[https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html U.S. Decennial Census]\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 5,524 people, 2,290 households, and 1,470 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 1,197.6 people per square mile (462.7/km\u00b2). There were 2,568 housing units at an average density of 556.7 per square mile (215.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 52.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 45.8% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.4% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.81% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.31% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.54% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.80% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 Census Fact Finder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=Search&geo_id=86000US29520&_geoContext=01000US%7C86000US29520&_street=&_county=cheraw&_cityTown=cheraw&_state=04000US45&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=860&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null%3Anull&_keyword=&_industry=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216041450/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=Search&geo_id=86000US29520&_geoContext=01000US%7C86000US29520&_street=&_county=cheraw&_cityTown=cheraw&_state=04000US45&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=860&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null:null&_keyword=&_industry=|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-16|publisher=US Census}}</ref>\n\nThere were 2,290 households out of which 31.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 25.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.8% were non-families. 33.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.32 and the average family size was 2.96.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 26.5% under the age of 18, 7.6% from 18 to 24, 24.4% from 25 to 44, 22.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years. For every 100 females, there were 78.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 70.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $21,897, and the median income for a family was $31,136. Males had a median income of $27,405 versus $22,003 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $13,801. About 27.3% of families and 32.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 43.1% of those under age 18 and 21.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\nCheraw was the center of an urban cluster with a total population of 9,069 according to the 2000 census.  In 2015, Cheraw and the surrounding areas of Chesterfield County had a population of 14,944 with a median income of $41,170 according to the U.S. Bureau of Census, American Community Survey's 5-year estimate and the Bureau of Statistics in Columbia, SC.\n\n==Education==\n* [https://cps.chesterfieldschools.org/ Cheraw Primary School]\n* [https://cis.chesterfieldschools.org/ Cheraw Intermediate School]\n* [https://lms.chesterfieldschools.org/ Long Middle School]\n* [https://chs.chesterfieldschools.org/ Cheraw High School]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/St-Davids-School/120326131318192 St. Davids School (PreK3 to Kindergarten)]\n* [http://fcacheraw.com/ Faith Christian Academy]\n* [http://jesusislordchristianschool.com/ Jesus is Lord Christian School]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Patrick N. L. Bellinger]], Vice admiral and [[Naval aviation]] pioneer\n* [[Jaron Brown]], Cheraw High School and Clemson University graduate; NFL WR for the Arizona Cardinals and Seattle Seahawks\n* [[William P. Burch]] (1846-1926), [[National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame|U.S. Racing Hall of Fame]] Thoroughbred horse trainer\n*Elder J.E. Burch, minister and musician.\n* [[Fisher DeBerry]], football head coach, [[Air Force Falcons|Air Force]] 1984-2006, and member of [[College Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Dizzy Gillespie]], jazz trumpet player, bandleader, singer, and composer; along with [[Charlie Parker]] and others, credited with innovations that began the [[bebop]] style\n* [[Parson James]], singer/songwriter, best known for the song \"[[Stole the Show]]\" with Norwegian DJ [[Kygo]]\n* [[Donald Malloy]], gospel singer/musician\n* [[Cliff Matthews]], Cheraw High School and University of South Carolina graduate; NFL DE/DT Atlanta Falcons 2011- 2015, Tampa Bay Buccaneers 2016, Atlanta Falcons 2016\n*Zachery Michael, government official in the Trump Administration; chief of staff at Department of Energy; former Associate Director of Intergovernmental Affairs at The White House\n* [[David Thornton (actor)|David Thornton]], actor, spouse of singer-songwriter [[Cyndi Lauper]]\n<!-- *** INSTRUCTIONS FOR NOTABLE PEOPLE SECTIONS ***\nWhen you add a name in this section, it's YOUR responsibility to ensure all of the following for each person:\n 1) Insert person into list sorted by last name (surname).\n 2) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Bio]] requirements to ensure notability (see [[Wikipedia:Notability]]).\n 3) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Verifiability]] requirements to verify their notability and prove they resided in the city.\n 4) If the person has a Wikipedia article, then wikilink the persons name to the correct wikipedia article, otherwise add citation reference(s) to prove notability and attended the school (see [[Wikipedia:Citing sources]]).\n\n*** END OF INSTRUCTIONS *** -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Chesterfield County, South Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Confederate War Sites: Cheraw, South Carolina'', Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2000.\n* ''Old St. David's Church'',  Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2000.\n* ''A Guide to the Cheraw Historic District'',  Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2006.\n* ''Cheraw and the American Revolution'', Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2003.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cheraw.com/ Town of Cheraw official website]\n* [http://cherawchamber.com/ Cheraw Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Chesterfield County, South Carolina}}\n{{Marlboro County, South Carolina}}\n{{South Carolina}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Chesterfield County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Towns in South Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cheraw, South Carolina\n|settlement_type          = [[Town]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = CherawSC.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = SCMap-doton-Cheraw.PNG\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Cheraw, South Carolina\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[South Carolina]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in South Carolina|Counties]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Chesterfield County, South Carolina|Chesterfield]], [[Marlboro County, South Carolina|Marlboro]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 14.1\n|area_land_km2            = 14.0\n|area_water_km2           = 0.1\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 5851\n|population_density_km2   = 416.6\n|population_density_sq_mi =\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 51\n|elevation_ft             = 167\n|coordinates              = {{coord|34|41|48|N|79|53|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 29520\n|area_code                = [[Area codes 843 and 854|843, 854]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 45-13600<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1247267<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  = {{URL|www.cheraw.com}}\n|footnotes                = \n}}\n\n[[Image:Cheraw Town Hall.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Historic Town Hall in downtown Cheraw]]\n[[Image:Cheraw British Grave.jpg|thumb|right|The grave marker for a British soldier in St.&nbsp;David's Cemetery]]\n\n'''Cheraw''' ({{IPAc-en|t\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0254\u02d0}} {{respell|ch\u0259|RAW|'}}, {{IPAc-en|local|\u0283|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u0254\u02d0}} {{respell|sh\u0259|RAW|'}}) is a town on the [[Pee Dee River]] in [[Chesterfield County, South Carolina|Chesterfield]] County [[South Carolina]], United States. The population was 5,851 at the 2010 census and has the lowest per capita income level of any municipality of 5,000 or more residents in the Pee Dee region.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4513600| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Census Summary File 1 (G001): Cheraw town, South Carolina| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=July 1, 2015| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213045507/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US4513600| archive-date=February 13, 2020| url-status=dead}}</ref> It has been nicknamed \"The Prettiest Town in Dixie\". The harbor tug ''[[USS Cheraw (YTB-802)|USS Cheraw]]'' was named in the town's honor.\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nWhen the first Europeans arrived in the area it was inhabited by the [[Cheraw]] and [[Pee Dee people|Pee Dee]] [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|American Indian]] tribes. The Cheraw lived near the waterfall hill, near present-day Cheraw, but by the 1730s they had been devastated by new infectious disease inadvertently carried by the European traders. Survivors joined the [[Catawba people|Catawba Confederacy]] for safety and left their name in history. Only a few scattered Cheraw families remained by the time of the [[American Revolution]]. A few European settlers entered their territory in the 1730s, forced upriver when the [[Wales|Welsh]] came to claim the Welsh [[Baptist]] lands granted by the English government in the area around [[Society Hill, South Carolina|Society Hill]]. Many of the early settlers of the 1740s in Cheraw were ethnic [[English people|English]], [[Scottish people|Scots]], [[French people|French]] [[Huguenots]], or [[Irish people|Scots-Irish]].\n\nBy 1750, Cheraw had become an established Anglo-American village with a growing river trade, one of the first inland villages. It was one of only six places in South Carolina that appeared on English maps at the time. In the 1760s, Joseph and Eli Kershaw were granted the part of Cheraw that is now the downtown historic district. The Kershaws laid out a formal street system. By 1830 settlers lined all the streets with rows of [[Ulmus americana|elms]]. The Kershaws originally called the town \"Chatham\", but people never accepted this name, continuing to call it \"Cheraw\" or \"Cheraw Hill\".\n\n===American Revolution===\nThere was a lack of organization and rule during the beginning of the 1740s in the backcountry of South Carolina. This lack of organization and unrest was an underlying cause of the resentment people of these areas felt toward the British Crown. In the Pee Dee area, planters organized a group called [[War of the Regulation|the Regulators]] to help bring order to the area. In 1768 [[St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery|St. David's Parish]], the last [[Anglican Church]] built in South Carolina under [[King George III]], was established to help serve the civic and religious needs of the Cheraw area. Later a judicial district and courthouse were established to help deal with the problem of order. However, there was still much discontent with the ruling authority, and in May 1776 the grand jury of the Cheraws District Two declared its independence from [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]].\n\nMany area men played prominent roles in the [[American Revolution]]. They included Claudius Pegues, General Henry W. Harrington, the Ellerbe brothers, Philip Pledger, and Eli Kershaw. There was much unrest in the area during this time because Cheraw fell into part of the British strategic line of defense, where [[garrison]]s were built to control revolutionaries and to encourage [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|loyalists]]. Other towns in this line of defense included [[Camden, South Carolina]], and [[Augusta, Georgia]]. Cheraw also became a strategic point for the Americans. Military activity was especially heavy in Cheraw and surrounding counties from 1780-1781. During the Revolutionary War, [[St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery|St. David's Church]] was used as a hospital for British troops that operated under [[Lord Cornwallis]]'s command and as quarters for the South Carolina militia. In December 1780, just across from Cheraw, American commander General [[Nathanael Greene]] set up a \"camp of repose\" to rest and train his men.\n\n===Early 19th century===\nIn 1819, the first [[steamboat]] came up river, and along with it a burst of prosperity because of expanded trade. Cheraw was incorporated as a town in 1820. The main crops from the Cheraw area were [[Maize|corn]], [[cotton]], [[tobacco]], [[rice]] and [[indigo]]. Cheraw had the largest cotton market between [[Georgetown, South Carolina]], and [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]. Because of the cotton trade, the town boasted the largest bank in South Carolina outside of [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]] before the Civil War. Despite a serious fire in 1835, by 1850 the town was a prosperous center of trade.\n\n===Civil War===\n<!-- Missing image removed: [[Image:Cheraw Confederate Monument.jpg|thumb|right|The Confederate Monument in Cheraw is the oldest in the country.]] -->\nLeading up to the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Cheraw citizens played a key role in South Carolina's secession from the Union. On November 19, 1860, the first call for secession in a public meeting was made at the Chesterfield County Courthouse. John A. Inglis of Cheraw was in attendance. He later introduced the resolution for South Carolina to secede. Inglis was also named the chairman of the committee that wrote the document for South Carolina's secession.\n\nFrom the beginning of the war, Cheraw was known as a place of refuge and a storehouse for valuables. In March 1865, General [[William T. Sherman]] brought his [[Union Army|Union]] troops to Cheraw for several days. One Union soldier said that they found Cheraw to be \"a pleasant town and an old one with the Southern aristocratic bearing.\" Sherman used this as a time to gain more control over his men. No private dwellings or public buildings in Cheraw were destroyed by Sherman and his troops. However, an accidental explosion of captured gunpowder at the river hill burned the Cheraw business district. The county courthouse in [[Chesterfield, South Carolina|Chesterfield]] was burned in this event, resulting in the loss of many records. Thus, it is difficult to date many of the historic properties.\n\nDuring the Civil War, St.&nbsp;David's Church was used as a hospital by both the [[Confederate States Army|Confederate]] and Union armies. Some troops from both armies were buried there. The first Confederate monument was erected there in 1867, a claim disputed by [[Confederate Memorial (Romney, West Virginia)|Romney, West Virginia]]. Originally, the monument did not mention the Confederate soldiers because the area was still occupied by Federal troops.\n\n===20th century to present===\n\nThe Civil War caused great economic hardship in Cheraw, as it did in the entire South. However, by the early 1900s, prosperity began to return to Cheraw. The Great Depression again brought change. [[Cheraw State Park]] and Sandhills State Forest were both founded in the 1930s. By the 1950s and 1960s the groundwork was laid for industrial growth. By the end of the 20th century, Cheraw had a balanced industrial base while maintaining its historic charm, architectural treasures and natural resources.\n\nIn November, 1941, Cheraw saw pretend combat in its streets during the Battle of Pee Dee River, Phase 1 of the Carolina Maneuvers.  General George Patton's 2nd Armored Division was the (Red) attacking force versus Major General Charles F. Thompson's I Corps defending (Blue).  Tanks from Patton's division penetrated the defenses and entered the city center to be met by defending anti-tank guns.  It was determined that Red's tanks were successful and Blue forces were forced to withdraw from the town.<ref>Page 139, \"The U.S. Army GHQ Maneuvers of 1941\", Christopher R. Gabel,</ref>\n\nIn addition to St. David's Episcopal Church and Cemetery, the [[Cheraw Historic District]] and [[Robert Smalls School]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref><ref name=\"nps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/nr/listings/20140314.htm|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|date=2014-03-14|work=Weekly List of Actions Taken on Properties: 3/03/14 through 3/07/14|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCheraw is located in eastern Chesterfield County at the [[Atlantic Seaboard fall line|fall line]] of the [[Pee Dee River]]. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|14.1|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|14.0|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.1|km2|order=flip|2}}, or 0.64%, is water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n[[U.S. Route 1]] passes through the center of the town, leading northeast {{convert|21|mi}} to [[Rockingham, North Carolina]], and southwest {{convert|55|mi}} to [[Camden, South Carolina|Camden]]. [[U.S. Route 52]] joins US 1 in the center of Cheraw but leads northwest {{convert|22|mi}} to [[Wadesboro, North Carolina]], and south {{convert|41|mi}} to [[Florence, South Carolina|Florence]]. [[South Carolina Highway 9]] also passes through the center of Cheraw, leading southeast {{convert|15|mi}} to [[Bennettsville, South Carolina|Bennettsville]] and west {{convert|12|mi}} to [[Chesterfield, South Carolina|Chesterfield]], the [[county seat]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|align=right\n|1880= 918\n|1890= 976\n|1900= 1151\n|1910= 2873\n|1920= 3150\n|1930= 3573\n|1940= 4497\n|1950= 4836\n|1960= 5171\n|1970= 5627\n|1980= 5654\n|1990= 5505\n|2000= 5524\n|2010= 5851\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=5619\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=September 11, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=[https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html U.S. Decennial Census]\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 5,524 people, 2,290 households, and 1,470 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 1,197.6 people per square mile (462.7/km\u00b2). There were 2,568 housing units at an average density of 556.7 per square mile (215.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 52.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 45.8% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.4% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.81% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.31% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.54% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.80% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|title=2000 Census Fact Finder|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=Search&geo_id=86000US29520&_geoContext=01000US%7C86000US29520&_street=&_county=cheraw&_cityTown=cheraw&_state=04000US45&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=860&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null%3Anull&_keyword=&_industry=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200216041450/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/SAFFFacts?_event=Search&geo_id=86000US29520&_geoContext=01000US%7C86000US29520&_street=&_county=cheraw&_cityTown=cheraw&_state=04000US45&_zip=&_lang=en&_sse=on&ActiveGeoDiv=geoSelect&_useEV=&pctxt=fph&pgsl=860&_submenuId=factsheet_1&ds_name=DEC_2000_SAFF&_ci_nbr=null&qr_name=null&reg=null:null&_keyword=&_industry=|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-16|publisher=US Census}}</ref>\n\nThere were 2,290 households out of which 31.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 25.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.8% were non-families. 33.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.32 and the average family size was 2.96.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 26.5% under the age of 18, 7.6% from 18 to 24, 24.4% from 25 to 44, 22.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.9% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years. For every 100 females, there were 78.7 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 70.7 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $21,897, and the median income for a family was $31,136. Males had a median income of $27,405 versus $22,003 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $13,801. About 27.3% of families and 32.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 43.1% of those under age 18 and 21.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\nCheraw was the center of an urban cluster with a total population of 9,069 according to the 2000 census.  In 2015, Cheraw and the surrounding areas of Chesterfield County had a population of 14,944 with a median income of $41,170 according to the U.S. Bureau of Census, American Community Survey's 5-year estimate and the Bureau of Statistics in Columbia, SC.\n\n==Education==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120323141403/http://schools.mychesterfieldcountyschools.com/index.aspx?nid=78 Cheraw Primary School]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120323141340/http://schools.mychesterfieldcountyschools.com/index.aspx?nid=71 Cheraw Intermediate School]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120323141348/http://schools.mychesterfieldcountyschools.com/index.aspx?nid=69 Long Middle School]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130815183438/http://schools.mychesterfieldcountyschools.com/index.aspx?nid=62 Cheraw High School]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130627033330/http://stdavidskids.com/ St. Davids School (PreK3 to Kindergarten)]\n* [http://fcacheraw.com/ Faith Christian Academy ]\n*  [http://jesusislordchristianschool.com/ Jesus is Lord Christian School]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Patrick N. L. Bellinger]], Vice admiral and [[Naval aviation]] pioneer\n* [[Jaron Brown]], Cheraw High School and Clemson University graduate; NFL WR for the Arizona Cardinals and Seattle Seahawks\n* [[William P. Burch]] (1846-1926), [[National Museum of Racing and Hall of Fame|U.S. Racing Hall of Fame]] Thoroughbred horse trainer\n*Elder J.E. Burch, minister and musician.\n* [[Fisher DeBerry]], football head coach, [[Air Force Falcons|Air Force]] 1984-2006, and member of [[College Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Dizzy Gillespie]], jazz trumpet player, bandleader, singer, and composer; along with [[Charlie Parker]] and others, credited with innovations that began the [[bebop]] style\n* [[Parson James]], singer/songwriter, best known for the song \"[[Stole the Show]]\" with Norwegian DJ [[Kygo]]\n* [[Donald Malloy]], gospel singer/musician\n* [[Cliff Matthews]], Cheraw High School and University of South Carolina graduate; NFL DE/DT Atlanta Falcons 2011- 2015, Tampa Bay Buccaneers 2016, Atlanta Falcons 2016\n*Zachery Michael, government official in the Trump Administration; chief of staff at Department of Energy; former Associate Director of Intergovernmental Affairs at The White House\n* [[David Thornton (actor)|David Thornton]], actor, spouse of singer-songwriter [[Cyndi Lauper]]\n<!-- *** INSTRUCTIONS FOR NOTABLE PEOPLE SECTIONS ***\nWhen you add a name in this section, it's YOUR responsibility to ensure all of the following for each person:\n 1) Insert person into list sorted by last name (surname).\n 2) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Bio]] requirements to ensure notability (see [[Wikipedia:Notability]]).\n 3) Each person MUST meet [[Wikipedia:Verifiability]] requirements to verify their notability and prove they resided in the city.\n 4) If the person has a Wikipedia article, then wikilink the persons name to the correct wikipedia article, otherwise add citation reference(s) to prove notability and attended the school (see [[Wikipedia:Citing sources]]).\n\n*** END OF INSTRUCTIONS *** -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Chesterfield County, South Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''Confederate War Sites: Cheraw, South Carolina'', Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2000.\n* ''Old St. David's Church'',  Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2000.\n* ''A Guide to the Cheraw Historic District'',  Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2006.\n* ''Cheraw and the American Revolution'', Cheraw Visitors Bureau, 2003.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cheraw.com/ Town of Cheraw official website]\n* [http://cherawchamber.com/ Cheraw Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Chesterfield County, South Carolina}}\n{{Marlboro County, South Carolina}}\n{{South Carolina}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Chesterfield County, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Towns in South Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Bdconley2", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated URLs for Education list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheraw,_South_Carolina"}
